1
00:01:16,792 --> 00:01:18,875
Replacement team's here, sir.

2
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:20,083
Right.

3
00:01:20,208 --> 00:01:22,250
Come on through.

4
00:01:23,625 --> 00:01:26,417
20 minutes and we were gonna
start looking for you.

5
00:01:26,542 --> 00:01:29,000
Yeah. It's really something out there.

6
00:01:29,208 --> 00:01:31,208
- You look a mess, sir.
- Yeah?

7
00:01:31,333 --> 00:01:33,375
Your turn next, Ginsburg.

8
00:01:40,125 --> 00:01:42,167
OK. I'll see you in 24.

9
00:01:42,333 --> 00:01:44,000
See you tomorrow.

10
00:01:48,667 --> 00:01:50,792
What was that you were you saying?

11
00:01:50,917 --> 00:01:54,583
You used to hear her chant
all night long. Om mahneypod me om.

12
00:01:54,708 --> 00:01:57,167
- Om mahneypod me om.
- Over the plants?

13
00:01:57,292 --> 00:02:00,583
She'd cup her hands over those seeds
and chant by the hour.

14
00:02:00,708 --> 00:02:03,792
She grew the most beautiful
wandoos you ever saw, man.

15
00:02:03,917 --> 00:02:05,958
Primo stuff. Resin city.

16
00:02:10,958 --> 00:02:13,000
Stand clear.

17
00:02:21,583 --> 00:02:25,042
The commander's been worried
about you. The roads must be a bear.

18
00:02:25,167 --> 00:02:27,375
- What roads?
- Visibility.

19
00:02:27,500 --> 00:02:32,208
Visibility? Bullshit. You guys haven't
been on time for the last six months.

20
00:02:32,333 --> 00:02:36,000
- I wrote you guys up in the logbook.
- Yeah. You're a prince, Bevan.

21
00:02:37,833 --> 00:02:39,875
Good night, gentlemen!

22
00:02:50,542 --> 00:02:52,792
So, that was like sinsemilia, right?

23
00:02:52,917 --> 00:02:56,625
Sinsemilla. This grass made
Thai stick taste like oregano.

24
00:02:56,792 --> 00:02:58,792
Lay you out flat, man.

25
00:03:02,875 --> 00:03:05,042
- Got a red light, sir.
- What on?

26
00:03:05,167 --> 00:03:07,208
Number eight. Warhead alarm.

27
00:03:07,333 --> 00:03:09,583
Give it a thump with your finger.

28
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:16,292
Alarm reset.

29
00:03:30,542 --> 00:03:34,917
Skybird, this is Dropkick with
a Red dash Alpha message in two parts.

30
00:03:35,042 --> 00:03:37,083
Break. Break. Red dash Alpha.

31
00:03:37,250 --> 00:03:39,792
- Stand by to copy message.
- Standing by.

32
00:03:39,917 --> 00:03:43,208
Romeo Oscar November Charlie

33
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:46,917
Tango Tango Lima Alpha.

34
00:03:47,042 --> 00:03:53,333
Authentication: 220040 Delta

35
00:03:53,500 --> 00:03:55,042
Lima.

36
00:03:55,167 --> 00:03:58,208
I have a valid message.
Stand by to authenticate.

37
00:03:58,333 --> 00:04:00,833
I agree with authentication also, sir.

38
00:04:17,500 --> 00:04:20,250
- Enter launch code.
- Entering launch code.

39
00:04:26,208 --> 00:04:29,833
- Launch order confirmed.
- Holy shit!

40
00:04:34,792 --> 00:04:39,125
Target selection: complete.
Time on target sequence: complete.

41
00:04:39,292 --> 00:04:42,667
- Yield selection: complete.
- Begin countdown. Tminus 60.

42
00:04:42,792 --> 00:04:45,875
- All right. Let's do it. Insert launch key.
- Stand by.

43
00:04:46,708 --> 00:04:49,583
- Launch key inserted.
- Roger.

44
00:04:49,708 --> 00:04:52,958
On my mark... rotate launch key to Set.

45
00:04:53,958 --> 00:04:56,667
Three... two... one...

46
00:04:57,458 --> 00:04:59,792
- Mark.
- Tminus 50.

47
00:05:09,917 --> 00:05:11,958
Roger. At Set.

48
00:05:18,083 --> 00:05:19,833
- Sir?
- Tminus 40.

49
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:23,458
- Enable missiles.
- Number one enabled. Two enabled.

50
00:05:23,583 --> 00:05:26,833
- Three enabled.
- Get somebody on the goddamn phone.

51
00:05:29,750 --> 00:05:31,208
Seven... eight...

52
00:05:33,208 --> 00:05:35,167
Nine...

53
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:39,625
Ten. All missiles enabled.

54
00:05:39,750 --> 00:05:43,958
- Get me Wing Command Post. Direct line.
- That's not the correct procedure.

55
00:05:44,083 --> 00:05:47,500
- Try SAC Headquarters on the HF.
- That's not the procedure.

56
00:05:47,625 --> 00:05:51,917
I want somebody on the goddamn phone
before I kill 20 million people.

57
00:05:55,750 --> 00:05:57,292
T minus 20.

58
00:05:57,417 --> 00:06:01,333
I got nothin' here! They might
have been knocked out already.

59
00:06:01,458 --> 00:06:03,083
Right.

60
00:06:03,208 --> 00:06:06,375
On my mark,
rotate launch keys to Launch.

61
00:06:06,542 --> 00:06:08,750
Roger. Ready to go to Launch.

62
00:06:08,917 --> 00:06:11,250
- Fourteen...
- Thirteen... twelve...

63
00:06:11,375 --> 00:06:12,667
Eleven...

64
00:06:15,708 --> 00:06:19,208
Seven... six...

65
00:06:19,333 --> 00:06:21,667
- Five...
- Sir, we have a launch order.

66
00:06:21,792 --> 00:06:24,917
- Three... two...
- Put your hand on the key, sir.

67
00:06:25,083 --> 00:06:26,917
One... Launch!

68
00:06:29,667 --> 00:06:34,083
- Sir, we are at launch! Turn your key!
- I'm sorry. I'm so sorry.

69
00:06:34,250 --> 00:06:36,833
Turn your key, sir!

70
00:08:26,208 --> 00:08:28,375
They're cleared. Go ahead and open it up.

71
00:08:32,083 --> 00:08:36,500
- Hello. I'm Pat Healy.
- I'm Lyle Watson. This is Arthur Cabot.

72
00:08:36,625 --> 00:08:41,250
I'm Pat Healy, Dr McKittrick's assistant.
I've got some passes for you here.

73
00:08:41,417 --> 00:08:44,250
We had scheduled a meeting
pending your arrival.

74
00:08:44,375 --> 00:08:47,083
If you have any questions,
feel free to ask me.

75
00:08:47,208 --> 00:08:50,333
I'd be happy to fill you in
if there's any way I can.

76
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:47,042
They're here.

77
00:09:47,167 --> 00:09:48,750
Good.

78
00:09:48,875 --> 00:09:50,375
Let's go.

79
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:55,583
Cabot and Watson came alone.
No senators. No congressmen.

80
00:09:55,750 --> 00:10:00,083
I wish they'd brought a few senators.
I'd like to tell 'em what's going on here.

81
00:10:00,208 --> 00:10:02,917
John, please! Don't start that right away.

82
00:10:03,042 --> 00:10:05,625
I had them on the phone
and they're calmed down.

83
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:13,000
Well, are we positive that these men had
no way of knowing this was only a test?

84
00:10:13,125 --> 00:10:16,750
Lyle, for God's sakes! How many times
are we gonna go through this?

85
00:10:17,042 --> 00:10:20,333
- It doesn't make any difference.
- I've spoken to these men.

86
00:10:20,458 --> 00:10:22,792
They all believed it was the real deal.

87
00:10:22,917 --> 00:10:25,667
Look, we gotta be on a plane
in less than an hour.

88
00:10:25,792 --> 00:10:29,958
I have to explain to the president
why 22% of his missile commanders

89
00:10:30,083 --> 00:10:34,833
failed to launch their missiles. What
am I supposed to say? 22% isn't so bad?

90
00:10:34,958 --> 00:10:39,667
The president knows that I am fully
responsible for the men in my command.

91
00:10:39,792 --> 00:10:43,750
I've ordered a re-evaluation of
our psychological screening procedure.

92
00:10:43,875 --> 00:10:46,208
Wait a minute. Excuse me, General.

93
00:10:46,333 --> 00:10:49,417
We can't ask these men
to go back to the president

94
00:10:49,583 --> 00:10:53,875
with a lot of headshrinker horseshit!
You can't screen out human response!

95
00:10:54,000 --> 00:10:58,792
Those men know what it means to turn
the keys, and some are just not up to it!

96
00:10:58,917 --> 00:11:01,583
Now, it's as simple as that!

97
00:11:05,125 --> 00:11:08,042
I think we oughta take
the men out of the loop.

98
00:11:08,167 --> 00:11:11,750
- Mr McKittrick, you're out of line, sir.
- Why am I out of line?

99
00:11:11,875 --> 00:11:13,417
Excuse me!

100
00:11:14,708 --> 00:11:18,167
I'm sorry. I don't understand.
Take them out of the loop?

101
00:11:18,333 --> 00:11:21,083
Gentlemen! We've had men in these silos

102
00:11:21,208 --> 00:11:24,750
since before any of you
were watching Howdy Doody.

103
00:11:27,083 --> 00:11:31,750
For myself, I sleep pretty well at night
knowing those boys are down there.

104
00:11:31,875 --> 00:11:36,000
General, we know they're fine men,
but in a nuclear war we can't afford

105
00:11:36,125 --> 00:11:38,917
to have missiles
lying dormant in those silos

106
00:11:39,042 --> 00:11:42,875
because those men refuse to turn
the keys when the computers tell 'em to!

107
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:45,208
You mean when
the president orders them to.

108
00:11:45,375 --> 00:11:50,083
The president will probably follow
the computer war plan. That's a fact!

109
00:11:50,208 --> 00:11:52,958
I imagine the Joint Chiefs
will have some input.

110
00:11:53,083 --> 00:11:55,708
- You're damn tootin'.
- Well, hell...

111
00:11:55,875 --> 00:11:58,333
In a surprise attack, there's no time.

112
00:11:58,458 --> 00:12:01,000
23 minutes from warning to impact.

113
00:12:01,125 --> 00:12:04,292
- Six minutes if it's sub-launched.
- Six minutes.

114
00:12:04,417 --> 00:12:08,250
That's barely enough time
for the president to make a decision.

115
00:12:08,375 --> 00:12:11,333
Once he makes the decision,
the computer should take over.

116
00:12:11,458 --> 00:12:15,208
Now, sir, I know that you've got
a plane waiting for you,

117
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:18,833
but if you could indulge me,
I'd like to show you something.

118
00:12:26,208 --> 00:12:29,667
These computers give instant access
to the state of the world.

119
00:12:29,792 --> 00:12:33,208
Troop movements, Soviet
missile tests, weather patterns.

120
00:12:33,417 --> 00:12:37,208
It all flows into this room,
and then into the WOPR computer.

121
00:12:37,333 --> 00:12:40,875
- WOPR? What is that?
- War Operation Plan Response.

122
00:12:41,000 --> 00:12:42,833
This is Mr Richter.

123
00:12:42,958 --> 00:12:46,833
Paul, would you like to tell
these gentlemen about the WOPR?

124
00:12:46,958 --> 00:12:51,458
Well, the WOPR spends all its time
thinking about World War Ill.

125
00:12:51,583 --> 00:12:58,833
24 hours a day, 365 days a year,
it plays an endless series of war games

126
00:12:58,958 --> 00:13:02,500
using all available information
on the state of the world.

127
00:13:02,625 --> 00:13:06,500
The WOPR has already fought
World War Ill, as a game,

128
00:13:06,667 --> 00:13:08,708
time and time again.

129
00:13:08,833 --> 00:13:12,042
It estimates Soviet responses
to our responses

130
00:13:12,167 --> 00:13:14,458
to their responses, and so on.

131
00:13:14,583 --> 00:13:17,167
Estimates damage. Counts the dead.

132
00:13:17,292 --> 00:13:20,042
Then it looks for ways
to improve its score...

133
00:13:20,208 --> 00:13:22,625
The point is that the key decisions

134
00:13:22,750 --> 00:13:25,875
of every option have already
been made by the WOPR.

135
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:29,667
So all this trillion-dollar hardware
is really at the mercy

136
00:13:29,792 --> 00:13:32,167
of those men with the little brass keys?

137
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:36,042
That's exactly right. Whose only problem
is that they're human beings.

138
00:13:36,167 --> 00:13:41,000
But in 30 days we could put in electronic
relays. Get the men out of the loop.

139
00:13:41,125 --> 00:13:42,750
Gentlemen...

140
00:13:43,917 --> 00:13:48,500
I wouldn't trust this overgrown pile of
microchips further than I could throw it.

141
00:13:48,667 --> 00:13:54,292
I don't know if you wanna trust the safety
of our country to some... silicon diode...

142
00:13:54,417 --> 00:13:58,042
Nobody is talking about entrusting
the safety of the nation

143
00:13:58,167 --> 00:14:00,208
to a machine, for God's sake!

144
00:14:00,333 --> 00:14:03,375
We'll keep control,
but here at the top where it belongs.

145
00:14:03,500 --> 00:14:04,917
All right, gentlemen.

146
00:14:05,042 --> 00:14:09,167
I think I'm going to recommend
McKittrick's idea to the president.

147
00:14:09,333 --> 00:14:11,792
And I'll get back to you on this.

148
00:14:13,625 --> 00:14:15,667
You won't regret this.

149
00:14:37,833 --> 00:14:40,042
OK. You had fries and a Coke, right?

150
00:14:58,625 --> 00:15:00,667
Damn!

151
00:15:03,167 --> 00:15:05,208
- Hi, David!
- Hi, Howie!

152
00:15:06,292 --> 00:15:08,333
- How's it going?
- Pretty good.

153
00:15:11,875 --> 00:15:14,708
- You wanna take this over? I gotta go.
- Sure!

154
00:15:14,833 --> 00:15:16,875
- Go ahead.
- Thanks!

155
00:15:20,542 --> 00:15:22,583
- Bye, David!
- Bye!

156
00:15:32,125 --> 00:15:36,042
All right. Question number two.

157
00:15:36,167 --> 00:15:44,042
Seeds that are germinated in water
before they are planted will... what?

158
00:15:44,208 --> 00:15:46,500
- Robert?
- Sprout roots?

159
00:15:46,667 --> 00:15:48,333
Ah! David!

160
00:15:48,458 --> 00:15:52,958
Nice of you to join us.
Oh, David. I have a little present for you.

161
00:16:03,708 --> 00:16:07,083
Question number four.
In the history of science,

162
00:16:07,208 --> 00:16:10,792
novel and innovative concepts
occasionally arise

163
00:16:10,917 --> 00:16:13,417
from sudden left-field inspiration.

164
00:16:13,542 --> 00:16:15,292
Miss Mack...

165
00:16:15,458 --> 00:16:18,792
Could you tell us your answer
to question number four?

166
00:16:18,917 --> 00:16:22,458
Why do nitrogen nodules
cling to the roots of plants?

167
00:16:25,042 --> 00:16:27,083
Love?

168
00:16:30,167 --> 00:16:34,708
Jennifer, what do you know about
nitrogen nodules that we don't?

169
00:16:34,833 --> 00:16:38,333
Some bit of salacious info
to which you alone are privy?

170
00:16:38,958 --> 00:16:41,000
- No.
- I see.

171
00:16:41,125 --> 00:16:44,417
No, you didn't know
the correct answer - symbiosis.

172
00:16:45,875 --> 00:16:48,958
Because you don't pay attention in class.

173
00:16:52,583 --> 00:16:54,625
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

174
00:16:54,792 --> 00:17:00,042
There seems to be a lot of confusion on
this next question - asexual reproduction.

175
00:17:01,333 --> 00:17:03,375
Could someone tell me, please

176
00:17:03,458 --> 00:17:08,833
who first suggested the idea
of reproduction without sex?

177
00:17:17,083 --> 00:17:18,750
- Miss Mack!
- Yes?

178
00:17:18,875 --> 00:17:21,500
What is so amusing?

179
00:17:24,583 --> 00:17:25,917
What?

180
00:17:26,042 --> 00:17:28,750
All right, Lightman.

181
00:17:28,875 --> 00:17:34,083
Maybe you can tell us who first suggested
the idea of reproduction without sex.

182
00:17:34,208 --> 00:17:36,625
Your wife?

183
00:17:40,708 --> 00:17:43,000
Get out, Lightman! Get out!

184
00:17:51,333 --> 00:17:55,208
Mr Ligget wants me to discuss
my attitude problem with Mr Kessler.

185
00:17:55,333 --> 00:17:58,667
I think Mr Kessler's getting tired
of your attitude problem.

186
00:17:58,833 --> 00:18:00,458
Me, too.

187
00:18:31,333 --> 00:18:34,708
Lightman. What a... surprise.

188
00:18:34,833 --> 00:18:36,875
Won't you come in?

189
00:18:51,875 --> 00:18:53,917
Hi!

190
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:55,042
Hi!

191
00:18:55,167 --> 00:18:58,208
Sorry if I got you in trouble.
I couldn't stop laughing.

192
00:18:58,333 --> 00:19:00,375
That's OK. You were perfect.

193
00:19:00,500 --> 00:19:02,542
- I was?
- Yeah.

194
00:19:02,667 --> 00:19:04,708
- You want a ride home?
- Yeah.

195
00:19:06,833 --> 00:19:08,875
Hop on.

196
00:19:16,083 --> 00:19:19,375
- So you got an F on that test today, too?
- Yep.

197
00:19:19,500 --> 00:19:22,292
Guess we're both gonna be
stuck in summer school.

198
00:19:22,417 --> 00:19:25,333
- Not me.
- Why not? You have to make up biology.

199
00:19:26,167 --> 00:19:28,417
- I don't think so.
- Why not?

200
00:19:30,042 --> 00:19:33,125
- Why not? Come on! Tell me. Why not?
- Make a left.

201
00:19:33,250 --> 00:19:36,375
Why don't you come up to my house
and I'll show you?

202
00:19:36,542 --> 00:19:38,583
What are you gonna show me?

203
00:19:38,708 --> 00:19:41,875
I'm gonna show you.
I'll show you how you do it.

204
00:19:43,292 --> 00:19:46,000
- Hi, Bo!
- Oh! Hi, Bo!

205
00:19:46,125 --> 00:19:48,167
Hey, Bo! How you doin'?

206
00:20:05,708 --> 00:20:07,750
My room's upstairs.

207
00:20:07,875 --> 00:20:10,958
- Your parents aren't home?
- No. They both work.

208
00:20:29,167 --> 00:20:31,208
A little mess.

209
00:20:31,333 --> 00:20:33,375
It's OK. You should see my room.

210
00:20:42,875 --> 00:20:45,792
- You're really into computers, huh?
- Yeah.

211
00:20:50,292 --> 00:20:54,542
- What are you doing?
- I'm dialing into the school's computer.

212
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:11,542
They change the password every couple
of weeks, but I know where they write it.

213
00:21:25,167 --> 00:21:27,208
- Are those your grades?!
- Yeah.

214
00:21:28,125 --> 00:21:30,708
I don't think that I deserved an F, do you?

215
00:21:34,583 --> 00:21:37,208
- You can't do that!
- Already done.

216
00:21:39,833 --> 00:21:42,875
- Do you have a middle initial?
- K. Katherine.

217
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:50,917
Those are my grades.

218
00:21:51,042 --> 00:21:54,833
- How can anybody get a D in home EC?
- That's none of your business.

219
00:21:54,958 --> 00:21:57,333
- Can you erase this?
- No. It's too late.

220
00:21:57,458 --> 00:21:59,333
What are you doing?

221
00:21:59,458 --> 00:22:03,375
- I'm changing your biology grade.
- No. You'll get me in trouble.

222
00:22:03,500 --> 00:22:07,458
Nobody can find out. You got a C!
Now you won't go to summer school.

223
00:22:07,583 --> 00:22:09,708
- Change it back.
- Why? They can't...

224
00:22:09,833 --> 00:22:13,000
- I said change it back.
- OK. OK.

225
00:22:21,208 --> 00:22:23,125
I guess I'd better get going.

226
00:22:24,667 --> 00:22:26,708
Thanks for the ride.

227
00:22:27,458 --> 00:22:29,667
Yeah. OK. Bye.

228
00:22:29,833 --> 00:22:31,833
Bye.

229
00:23:31,375 --> 00:23:35,583
Get down. Get down. You've already
had your dinner. Now just sit.

230
00:23:35,708 --> 00:23:37,792
Sit! Stay!

231
00:23:37,917 --> 00:23:40,708
- Don't forget to take out the garbage.
- David.

232
00:23:40,833 --> 00:23:43,708
- Put that lid on real tight.
- I know, Ma.

233
00:23:45,417 --> 00:23:48,125
Yes, they will carry back on the second.

234
00:23:49,417 --> 00:23:52,917
Sure. I think we can really work out
some creative financing.

235
00:23:54,708 --> 00:23:56,750
Oh, but you've gotta see it!

236
00:23:56,917 --> 00:23:59,625
There's a Jacuzzi
in the master bedroom...

237
00:24:11,250 --> 00:24:13,417
Oh, sure. We can work that out.

238
00:24:14,417 --> 00:24:18,625
That is true. You'll have a balloon
payment at the end of five years.

239
00:24:18,750 --> 00:24:22,167
